# PART 1 · Thinking in Components

## Stop Seeing a "Page." Start Seeing "Boxes."

Look at your SkyCast screenshot. Don't look at the whole thing. Instead:

1. **Find the biggest boxes.** You can see two columns — a left side and a right side. Those are two components.
2. **Find the boxes inside those boxes.** The left column has a big weather card on top, a grid of small cards in the middle, and a sun/moon section at the bottom. Those are three more components.
3. **Find the repeated patterns.** The grid has 6 identical-looking cards. The right side has 7 identical-looking rows. Each of those is ONE component, used multiple times.

That's it. That's "thinking in components." You just zoomed in from the outside, layer by layer, like opening a Russian nesting doll.

## The Three Rules: When to Make a Component

### Rule 1 — The "I See Twins" Rule (Reusability)

If you see the same visual pattern appear MORE THAN ONCE on screen, it MUST be a component.

**In SkyCast:**
- The 6 small stat boxes → ONE `StatCard` component, used 6 times with different data
- The 7 forecast rows → ONE `ForecastRow` component, used 7 times with different data
- The 2 sun/moon rows → ONE `AstroRow` component, used twice

### Rule 2 — The "One Job" Rule (Single Responsibility)

A component should do exactly one thing. If you can describe it in one short sentence, it's the right size.

**Good examples:**
- `SearchBar` → "lets the user type a city name" ✅
- `StatCard` → "displays one weather metric with an icon" ✅
- `TabGroup` → "lets the user pick Today, Tomorrow, or 10 Days" ✅

**Bad example:**
- `WeatherPageLeftSideWithSearchAndStatsAndSunMoon` → Too many jobs. Break it up. ❌

### Rule 3 — The "It's Getting Cluttered" Rule (Complexity Isolation)

Even if something is used only ONCE, if it's complex (lots of markup, logic, or styling), pull it into its own component. This is about keeping files readable.

**In SkyCast:** The Sun & Moon arc with the SVG curved line is only used once, but it's visually complex enough to be isolated into `ArcVisualization`.

## When Something Should NOT Be a Component

- A single line of text like "Feels Like 35°" → just put it inside `CurrentWeatherHero`
- A decorative horizontal line → use CSS
- Something with only 2-3 lines of markup AND no reuse potential → inline it
- A CSS wrapper with no logic → use a regular HTML element with a class name

> [!TIP]
> **The naming test:** Try to give it a name. If you can say "`StatCard`" or "`ForecastRow`" and another developer would immediately picture what it looks like — great, it's a component. If the best name you can come up with is "`SmallBlueBox`" — it's probably not worth being a component.

