# PART 3 · Parent-Child Relationships

## The Manager-Worker Mental Model

Every component relationship in React follows a simple pattern:

- **The Parent (Manager)** decides WHAT to show and WHERE. It holds data and passes it down.
- **The Child (Worker)** decides HOW to show it. It receives props and renders them beautifully.

### Concrete Examples from SkyCast

**`StatsGrid` is the Manager of `StatCard`:**

```
StatsGrid (Manager) says:
  "I'm going to arrange 6 cards in a 3-column grid.
   Card 1 gets: icon=air, label=Air Quality, value=156
   Card 2 gets: icon=wind, label=Wind, value=1 mph
   Card 3 gets: icon=droplet, label=Humidity, value=54%
   ... and so on."

StatCard (Worker) says:
  "I don't care how many siblings I have.
   I don't care about the grid layout.
   I don't care what city this is for.
   Just give me icon, label, and value.
   I'll make them look beautiful."
```

**`ForecastList` is the Manager of `ForecastRow`:**

```
ForecastList (Manager) says:
  "I have an array of 7 hourly forecasts.
   I'll create one ForecastRow per item.
   Row 1 gets: time=1AM, condition=Mostly Cloudy, temp=12°C
   Row 2 gets: time=2AM, condition=Mostly Cloudy, temp=12°C
   ... and so on."

ForecastRow (Worker) says:
  "I show one horizontal row with the data I'm given.
   I have no idea what's in the rows above or below me.
   That's not my job."
```

**`App` is the Manager of EVERYTHING:**

```
App (CEO) says:
  "I hold the master weather data for whatever city was searched.
   I send current-weather data to the left side.
   I send forecast data to the right side.
   I send the city name to the navbar.
   Nobody fetches their own data — everyone gets it from me."
```

### Why This Matters

Because each worker is completely independent of its context:
- `StatCard` could be used in a completely different app (a fitness dashboard, a stock tracker) without changing a single thing inside it.
- `ForecastRow` has no idea it lives inside a weather app. It just renders whatever time, icon, and temperature it receives.

**This is component reusability — the entire point of React.**

---

# PART 4 · Props — Data Flowing Down

## The Waterfall Rule

```
        🏔️ App (holds ALL the data)
        |
        | props flow DOWN
        ↓
    ┌───────────┐
    |MainLayout |
    └─────┬─────┘
          |
    ┌─────┴──────┐
    ↓             ↓
LeftColumn    RightColumn
    ↓             ↓
StatsGrid    ForecastList
    ↓             ↓
StatCard     ForecastRow    ← leaf components (the bottom of the waterfall)
```

**Data flows DOWN. Always. Only.**

- `App` → `MainLayout` → `LeftColumn` → `StatsGrid` → `StatCard`
- `App` → `MainLayout` → `RightColumn` → `ForecastList` → `ForecastRow`
- A `StatCard` can NEVER reach over to `ForecastRow` and grab its data
- A `ForecastRow` can NEVER look up at `App` and ask for something

## What Props Each Component Gets (The Full Map)

### Navbar Area

| Component | Prop Name | Example Value | Given By |
|---|---|---|---|
| `LocationDisplay` | cityName | "Khulna, Bangladesh" | `Navbar` |
| `SearchBar` | onSearchSubmit | a function | `Navbar` (from `App`) |
| `ThemeToggle` | currentTheme | "light" | `Navbar` (from `App`) |
| `ThemeToggle` | onToggle | a function | `Navbar` (from `App`) |

### Left Column

| Component | Prop Name | Example Value | Given By |
|---|---|---|---|
| `CurrentWeatherHero` | temperature | 12 | `LeftColumn` |
| `CurrentWeatherHero` | unit | "F" | `LeftColumn` |
| `CurrentWeatherHero` | condition | "Rainy" | `LeftColumn` |
| `CurrentWeatherHero` | feelsLike | 35 | `LeftColumn` |
| `CurrentWeatherHero` | description | "There will be mostly sunny skies..." | `LeftColumn` |
| `CurrentWeatherHero` | icon | "partly-cloudy" | `LeftColumn` |
| `CurrentWeatherHero` | time | "2:59PM" | `LeftColumn` |
| `StatCard` | icon | "wind" | `StatsGrid` |
| `StatCard` | label | "Wind" | `StatsGrid` |
| `StatCard` | value | "1 mph" | `StatsGrid` |
| `AstroRow` | type | "sun" | `SunMoonCard` |
| `AstroRow` | riseTime | "5:43AM" | `SunMoonCard` |
| `AstroRow` | setTime | "5:43AM" | `SunMoonCard` |

### Right Column

| Component | Prop Name | Example Value | Given By |
|---|---|---|---|
| `TabGroup` | activeTab | "today" | `RightColumn` |
| `TabGroup` | onTabChange | a function | `RightColumn` |
| `ForecastRow` | time | "1AM" | `ForecastList` |
| `ForecastRow` | icon | "mostly-cloudy" | `ForecastList` |
| `ForecastRow` | condition | "Mostly Cloudy" | `ForecastList` |
| `ForecastRow` | temperature | 12 | `ForecastList` |
| `ForecastRow` | unit | "C" | `ForecastList` |
| `ForecastRow` | wind | "120km" | `ForecastList` |
| `ForecastRow` | humidity | "59%" | `ForecastList` |

> [!NOTE]
> **Pattern to notice:** The props for `StatCard` and `ForecastRow` are extremely generic. They're just `label`, `value`, `icon`, `time`, etc. They don't say anything weather-specific. That's what makes them reusable. If you named the props `windSpeed` inside `StatCard`, it would feel weird when you use the same component for "Humidity." Keep prop names generic.

