# PART 9 · File & Folder Structure

## How to Organize Your Project

Every component gets **two files**: a `.jsx` file (structure + logic) and a `.css` file (styling). Group them together.

```
src/
│
├── components/                    ← All your components live here
│   │
│   ├── Navbar/                    ← One folder per component (or group)
│   │   ├── Navbar.jsx
│   │   ├── Navbar.css
│   │   ├── BrandLogo.jsx          ← Small sub-components can share the folder
│   │   ├── SearchBar.jsx
│   │   ├── SearchBar.css
│   │   ├── ThemeToggle.jsx
│   │   ├── LocationDisplay.jsx
│   │   └── UserProfile.jsx
│   │
│   ├── CurrentWeatherHero/
│   │   ├── CurrentWeatherHero.jsx
│   │   └── CurrentWeatherHero.css
│   │
│   ├── StatsGrid/
│   │   ├── StatsGrid.jsx
│   │   ├── StatsGrid.css
│   │   ├── StatCard.jsx           ← Lives with its parent
│   │   └── StatCard.css
│   │
│   ├── SunMoonCard/
│   │   ├── SunMoonCard.jsx
│   │   ├── SunMoonCard.css
│   │   ├── AstroRow.jsx
│   │   └── AstroRow.css
│   │
│   ├── Forecast/
│   │   ├── RightColumn.jsx
│   │   ├── RightColumn.css
│   │   ├── ForecastHeader.jsx
│   │   ├── TabGroup.jsx
│   │   ├── TabGroup.css
│   │   ├── ForecastList.jsx
│   │   ├── ForecastList.css
│   │   ├── ForecastRow.jsx
│   │   └── ForecastRow.css
│   │
│   └── Layout/
│       ├── MainLayout.jsx
│       └── MainLayout.css
│
├── App.jsx                        ← Root component, holds state
├── App.css                        ← App-level layout styles
└── index.css                      ← Global styles, CSS variables, resets
```

### Why This Structure?

| Decision | Reason |
|---|---|
| One folder per "feature area" | Easy to find related files. Everything about "Forecast" is in one folder. |
| Small children live with their parents | `StatCard` lives inside `StatsGrid/` because it's only used there. |
| CSS file next to its component | You never have to hunt for the styles. `StatCard.jsx` → `StatCard.css` is right there. |
| `index.css` for globals | Color variables, font imports, CSS resets — things that apply everywhere. |

> [!TIP]
> **Beginner-friendly alternative:** If folders-per-feature feels overwhelming, you can start with a flat structure — ALL components directly inside `components/`. Refactor into folders later once you have more than 15 files. The flat approach works fine until your project grows.

---

# PART 10 · CSS Strategy for Components

## The Golden Rule: Each Component Owns Its Own Styles

`StatCard.css` should ONLY contain styles that affect `StatCard`. It should NOT try to style `ForecastRow` or the global background color.

### What Goes Where?

| File | What It Contains | Examples |
|---|---|---|
| `index.css` | Global resets, CSS variables, fonts, body background | Your lavender gradient background, font imports, color palette |
| `App.css` | The overall page layout | How `Navbar` and `MainLayout` sit on the page |
| `MainLayout.css` | The two-column grid | CSS Grid that puts LeftColumn and RightColumn side-by-side |
| `StatCard.css` | How ONE stat card box looks | Border-radius, padding, background, icon positioning |
| `ForecastRow.css` | How ONE forecast row looks | Horizontal layout, spacing between icon/temp/wind |

### The Color Palette (What to Define in `index.css`)

Looking at your design screenshots, these are the colors you need to define as CSS variables:

| Purpose | What It Looks Like | Variable Name Idea |
|---|---|---|
| Page background | Soft lavender/blue gradient | `--bg-gradient` |
| Card background | White or very slightly transparent white | `--card-bg` |
| Card border | Very subtle light blue/gray | `--card-border` |
| Primary text | Dark charcoal/navy (the temperatures, labels) | `--text-primary` |
| Secondary text | Medium gray (descriptions, secondary info) | `--text-secondary` |
| Active tab | White background with subtle shadow | `--tab-active-bg` |
| Inactive tab | Transparent with gray text | `--tab-inactive` |
| Red accent | The "See Monthly Cast" button and the red card borders in your wireframe | `--accent-red` |
| Blue accent | Soft blue used in borders and highlights | `--accent-blue` |

### Component Styling Rules

1. **Use class names, not IDs.** Each component's root element gets a class name matching the component: `class="stat-card"`, `class="forecast-row"`.
2. **Prefix your classes.** To avoid naming collisions, use the component name as a prefix: `stat-card-icon`, `stat-card-label`, `stat-card-value`.
3. **Don't use global tag selectors** like `div { }` or `p { }` in component CSS files. Those will leak to other components.

---

# PART 11 · The Fake Data Strategy

## Build the Entire UI Before Touching Any API

This is possibly the most important tactical advice in this entire guide. **Do not fetch real data from an API until your UI is 100% complete with fake data.**

### Why?

When you work with real APIs:
- API calls can fail (network errors, rate limits, wrong API key)
- The data shape might be unexpected (nested objects, missing fields)
- Debugging becomes harder — is the bug in your components or in your data?

By using fake data first, you eliminate ALL of these problems. Every bug you encounter is a component/CSS bug, which is much easier to fix.

### What Your Fake Data Looks Like (Conceptually)

Imagine you create a plain JavaScript object at the top of `App.jsx` that looks like this:

```
A fake data object shaped like:

{
  city: "Khulna, Bangladesh",
  current: {
    time: "2:59PM",
    temperature: 12,
    unit: "F",
    condition: "Rainy",
    feelsLike: 35,
    icon: "partly-cloudy",
    description: "There will be mostly sunny skies. The high will be 35°."
  },
  stats: {
    airQuality: 156,
    wind: "1 mph",
    humidity: "54%",
    visibility: "3 mi",
    pressure: "27.65 in",
    temperature: "66°"
  },
  astronomy: {
    sun: { rise: "5:43AM", set: "5:43AM" },
    moon: { rise: "5:43AM", set: "5:43AM" }
  },
  forecast: {
    today: [
      { time: "1AM", condition: "Mostly Cloudy", temp: 12, wind: "120km", humidity: "59%", icon: "cloudy" },
      { time: "2AM", condition: "Mostly Cloudy", temp: 12, wind: "120km", humidity: "59%", icon: "cloudy" },
      ... 5 more rows
    ],
    tomorrow: [ ... different data ... ],
    tenDays: [ ... different data ... ]
  }
}
```

You hardcode this once, and the entire UI works perfectly with it. Every `StatCard` gets its props from this object. Every `ForecastRow` gets its data from the `forecast.today` array.

### The Swap

Later (Phase 6), you replace this fake object with real API data. Since the structure is the same, **nothing else needs to change.** All your components keep working exactly as before — they don't care if the data came from a hardcoded object or a real API.

