# PART 14 · React Docs → SkyCast Map

## ✅ Concepts You Already Know (Apply Them Immediately)

| React Docs Chapter | Where You'll Use It in SkyCast | Specific Example |
|---|---|---|
| **Your First Component** | Every single file in the tree diagram | `StatCard` is a component. `ForecastRow` is a component. You'll create ~14 of them. |
| **Importing & Exporting** | Every parent imports its children | `StatsGrid.jsx` imports `StatCard`. `App.jsx` imports `MainLayout`. `ForecastList.jsx` imports `ForecastRow`. |
| **Writing Markup with JSX** | The structure inside every component | Inside `StatCard`, you'll have JSX that creates the icon, the label text, and the value text, all arranged in a box. |
| **JavaScript in JSX** | Displaying dynamic values | Instead of writing "12°F" as text, you write `{temperature}°{unit}`. Instead of "Rainy", you write `{condition}`. The curly braces insert the JavaScript variable's value. |
| **Passing Props** | Literally everywhere | `StatsGrid` renders `StatCard` 6 times, each time passing different `label` and `value` props. `ForecastList` renders `ForecastRow` 7 times, each time passing different `time` and `temperature` props. |

## 📚 Concepts You're About to Learn (And Where They Appear)

| React Docs Chapter | Where You'll Use It in SkyCast | Specific Example |
|---|---|---|
| **Conditional Rendering** | Showing/hiding parts of the UI based on conditions | "IF `isLoading` is true, show a spinner. ELSE show the dashboard." — "IF the active tab is 'today', show hourly data. IF it's 'tomorrow', show tomorrow's data." — "IF the weather icon is 'sunny', render a sun image. IF it's 'rainy', render rain image." |
| **Rendering Lists** | The right panel's 7 forecast rows + the left panel's 6 stat cards | You'll have an array like `[{time: "1AM", temp: 12}, {time: "2AM", temp: 11}, ...]` and use `.map()` to generate one `ForecastRow` per array item. Same for `StatCard` — you could have a stats array and `.map()` over it. |
| **Keeping Components Pure** | Every "display" component | `StatCard` MUST produce the same output every time it receives the same `icon`, `label`, and `value`. It must NOT modify any variable outside itself. It must NOT trigger side effects. It's a pure function of its props. |
| **Your UI as a Tree** | The entire tree diagram in Part 2 | React organizes your components in a tree structure. Data flows from root to leaves. The tree determines what re-renders when state changes (Part 7). |

## 🔮 Concepts You Haven't Read Yet (But Will Need for Phases 4-5)

| Concept | Why You'll Need It | When |
|---|---|---|
| **useState** | To track active tab, theme, weather data, loading state | Phase 4 |
| **Event Handling** | To react when the user clicks a tab, types in search, toggles theme | Phase 4 |
| **useEffect** | To fetch weather data from an API when the app loads or city changes | Phase 5 |
| **Async/Await** | To handle the API call (network requests are asynchronous) | Phase 5 |

> [!NOTE]
> **You do NOT need to read about `useState`, `useEffect`, or event handling right now.** Phases 1-3 use only concepts you already know: JSX, components, importing/exporting, props. Get the entire UI built first, then learn the interactive concepts when you actually need them.

